@everyone Later this week, Feral File is launching support for crypto payments (USDC, ETH, and BTC).

We initially planned to launch this a few weeks ago, but we took some extra time to work through technical issues.

As part of this change:

> We will be using Stripe for credit card payments and Wyre to process crypto payments. We have revised our Terms for Artists and Collectors to reflect the new service.

> Feral File will accept Bitcoin (BTC), Ethereum (ETH), and USD Coin (USDC). Choose the Deposit function under "Account > Profile", and you'll be given an address to send a transaction to. When the transaction is finalized, your account will be credited with the appropriate amount of USDC funds.

> You will be able to withdraw a positive account balance in cryptocurrency (USDC, ETH, and BTC) at any time to an external wallet within "Account." Balances will be shown in USDC.

> We will no longer accept credit cards for artwork being resold by previous buyers. Credit card payments can be reversed for 60 days, which would open us to fraud.

As a reminder, our next exhibition "The Long Cut" featured 7 groundbreaking artists exploring the boundary between the real and the simulated, curated by Iris Long.

Please join us here, Thursday at 18:00 PDT (UTC-8) for a discussion around Feral File's draft Ethereum smart contracts.

Here are the key points:

—Each exhibition will have its own unique smart contract
—The contracts will be ERC-721 compliant
—Bitmark NFTs will be able to migrate to Ethereum (see: Bridge Flow).

We hope to get feedback from the community, make any necessary tweaks, and then finish our external security reviews.

As most of you know, Feral File has been minted on the public Bitmark chain. The Bitmark chain is not interoperable with the rest of the NFT ecosystem that has emerged around Ethereum. Our goal is to change this as fast as possible. In these contracts, we also offer the functionality for collectors to move their editions from the Bitmark chain into the Ethereum chain.

Casey Reas & Sean Moss-Pultz (CEO Bitmark)

I wanted to share a bit about our tech for this exhibition.
This time around we used 10 server instances. (Each one is a web server). We use K8s pods, on AWS (EC2). As it’s clear now, we were unable to keep up with the traffic.
For a bit of context, in the last exhibtion, we ran also 10 server instances. Even though we sold out in less than 3 minutes, we were no where near the capacity limit.
A week or so before this exhibition we detected bots experimenting with our system.
We made a number of fixes and they were all deployed for this time around. There was one person that we know was using a bot. But it failed.
When we opened we were seeing about 250 requests per second.
This amout traffic was totally unexpected.

Here's the recap of what happened: During the rush to get a lot of new code ready for this exhibition, we deployed the wrong version of our (new) payment server to production. We figured this out 30 minutes before the launch. We fixed the issue. Then deployed the new code. But this entire process finished just under five minutes after the launch. This caused a cascading set of problems that could only be manually fixed. It resulted in the super painful situation that people paid for artworks that were already sold.

@everyone To welcome 2023, we’re introducing new changes to our community Discord server to create a more enjoyable experience for everyone.

**1) Moving from Chat-focus to Forum Threads**

Feral File operates at a different pace. We do a couple of exhibitions per month, so we don’t expect our community to be around on the server at all times of day every day. Thus, we felt that allowing long term, gradual conversation to develop would create a friendly environment for new and current community members. We hope that forums allow for deeper exploration of our exhibitions and art-related topics brought up by our community.

Through each exhibition thread (example: https://discord.com/channels/768706944097058828/1058101057332461669) and our exhibition list (https://discord.com/channels/768706944097058828/1050133565142208542), you will be able to quickly find information around the exhibitions and how to keep conversations going with our artists, curators, and other community members.

If you do want to simply hang out and chat, welcome new members, discuss random things, we welcome this in live-chat and collector-talk.

**2) Technical Support is no longer handled on Discord**

We enjoy discussing the development of Feral File and Autonomy Digital Wallet App on Discord with you, but individual technical support should be handled securely and privately. This request relates to…

**3) Changes to keep you safe**

We are using various server rules to discourage non-serious users from joining the community. We want you to be safe and highly discourage communicating over DMs, including with us - in the past users have tried to emulate Bitmark employees. We believe these changes will foster a safe place for everyone to discuss art together. Web3 was built on the foundations of transparency, and we similarly echo this in our products. When in doubt, communicate publicly.

We always welcome feedback and will keep listening to make this a wonderful space for everyone.

@everyone I’ve got another exciting update to share: In the coming days, every Feral File artwork minted on Ethereum will have its own unique “Collection” on OpenSea. This will greatly improve discovery on secondary markets.

When we introduced our Ethereum bridge, we worked with OpenSea to map exhibitions onto Collections. That seemed right at the time. Each exhibition had its own smart contract. But in hindsight, our three-level hierarchy (exhibitions / artworks / editions) caused problems for search on OpenSea, as many of you told us. It also made it confusing to understand metrics for a specific artwork, such as volumes, floor values, and pricing.

These changes are propagating across OpenSea as I write. I can see that METASOTO (https://opensea.io/collection/metasoto-by-casey-reas) from Peer-to-Peer is already live now. As are others. You’ll see things updating in batches. If anything seems wrong, please let me know.
